Load data from both survey periods (2018 and 2019) and wrangle predator sub-set data into separate dfs called preds and predsum:

Variables:

Modelling predator abundance (response variable) against reef type (fixed effect predictor variable), with site as a random effect:

  1. Numbers of predators (response variable): This is count data and needs to be scaled against total fish assemblage size, so could convert into a proportion (0-1) but instead well scale inside the model using offset().
  2. Reef type (predictor variable (fixed effect)): Factor with 3 levels.
  3. Site (nested random effect): 4 sites per reef type, 12 total.
  4. Numbers of fish (scaling variable): Need to scale the model to account for total fish numbers

Note: Initially thought about including survey period as a fully crossed random effect, however there are only two levels within this variable making any variance partitioning meaningless (cant have variance between 2 observations - generally considered that 5 is the minimum). In theory could include as a fixed effect, however we are not really interested in it as a predictor and want to maintain model parsimony!

- Lots of zeros so perhaps will need a ZI term in the model. These are count data so expecting Poisson or neg binom distributions to work best. - Predator abundance high on pinnacles where we exclusively recorded the large schools of pelagic/semi-pelagic fishes (in particular S. qenie). Could look at transforming or adjusting the data, treating these as outliers and excluding. However, these observations may be ecologically important and the right GLMM error-family should handle these data.

Fit models

Basic GLMM with site as random factor. Will introduce offset later on. Trialled other error families but all poor fit: Gaussian, Poisson, Gamma, Beta (on %) etc

Model formulas

# Neg binom 2 (Neg binom 1 poor fit)
pred.glmmnb <- glmmTMB(No_Preds~Reeftype+(1|SiteCode), data=predsum, family=nbinom2())  
# ZI (on neg binom 2)
pred.glmmzi <- glmmTMB(No_Preds~Reeftype+(1|SiteCode), data=predsum, family=nbinom2(), ziformula=~1)
# Tweedie
pred.glmmt <- glmmTMB(No_Preds~Reeftype+(1|SiteCode), data=predsum, family=tweedie())

Source code for all models trialled if required (model comparisons etc)

-> So emmeans table suggests that pinnacles have more predators than both offshore emergent and near shore reefs, but that this is highly variable. What about if we take into account overall numbers of fishes?

Model tweaking

Now going to add the offset

pred.glmmnboff <- update(pred.glmmnb, ~ . + offset(log(No_Fish)))

Calculate emmeans (response scale - numbers of predators)

# Sort the contrast names out for plotting
# Turn into tibble first
abunresults <- emmeans(pred.glmmnboff, pairwise ~ Reeftype, transform='response') %>%
  confint() %>% 
  as_tibble

# Then change names
abunresults$contrasts$contrast <- recode(abunresults$contrasts$contrast,
       `Pinnacle - Offshore` = 'Pinnacle -\nOffshore  ',
       `Pinnacle - Nearshore` = 'Pinnacle -\nNearshore',
       `Offshore - Nearshore` = 'Offshore -\nNearshore')
# And convert back to emm object
abunresults <- abunresults %>% 
  as.list


# To copy out to excel
abunresults %>% 
  as.data.frame() %>% 
  tab_df()

Contrast back transformations

Pinnacle - Offshore exp(1.151) = 3.16 -> I think this means that on average there are 3 x more predators on pinnacles than on offshore reefs exp(0.228) = 1.26 -> Could be as little as 26% more exp(2.07) = 7.92 -> Or as much as 7.9 times more

Pinnacle - Near shore exp(1.315) = 3.72 -> and nearly 4 times more than on near shore reefs exp(0.331) = 1.4 -> could be as little as 40% more exp(2.30) = 10 -> Or as much as 10 times more

Plots

# emmeans figure
abunplotresults <- ggplot(abunresults$emmeans, aes(y=response,  x=Reeftype)) +
  geom_pointrange(aes(ymin=lower.CL,  ymax=upper.CL))+
  xlab('Reef type\n')+
  ylab('Mean no. of predators\nper transect (95% CI))')+
  theme_classic()+
  theme(axis.title.x = element_text(family="Arial", size=14, colour = 'black', vjust = -2),
        axis.title.y = element_text(family="Arial", size=14, colour = 'black', vjust=2.5),
        axis.text = element_text(family="Arial", size= 14, colour = 'black'))


# Contrasts figure
abunplotcontrasts <- ggplot(abunresults$contrasts, aes(y=estimate,  x=contrast)) +
  geom_pointrange(aes(ymin=lower.CL,  ymax=upper.CL))+
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype='dashed')+
  xlab('')+
  ylab('Contrasts estimates ( mean predator\nabundance per transect 95% CI)')+
  coord_flip()+
  theme_classic()+
  theme(axis.title.x = element_text(family="Arial", size=14, colour = 'black', vjust = -0.5),
        axis.text = element_text(family="Arial", size= 14, colour = 'black'))

# Plot together
fig <- grid.arrange(abunplotresults, abunplotcontrasts, nrow=1)

plot(fig)

# Save
ggsave(fig, filename= '../../output/rfigures/abund_fig.png', width=11,  height=4, dpi = 1000 )
